Hey Alexa, how many babies are named after you?¶

Visualizing the development of naming newborns "Alexa" in different countries over the last twenty years.

Notebook created for fun by Dynobo in 02/2020

1) Introduction¶

1.1) Preface¶

Recently, for the first time, I met a person named "Alexa" (it's a rare name in Germany). Also for the first time, I noticed what a beautiful name it is and how odd it feels, that a device by Amazon is called by the same name. It kinda felt unfair, because the young woman was there before the device, and probably now has to face a lot lame jokes.

That's how I got curious to investigate, what influence the appearance of the device has on the names if newborns...

1.2) Learnings¶

During this tiny data project I have learned a lot. And anyone who looks through this notebook may learn that as well.

  • The number of ways to publish a data set as simple as the names of newborns is amazingly high. The impact for re-use is quite high: E.g. I wouldn't try to use the data from England & Wales again, while working with the US and Canadian datasets was a joy.
  • I practised downloading and pre-processing data from various sources, mostly with pandas.
  • Creating appealing charts with matplotlib is not easy, but possible. (I'm not a info-designer, so I'm still not totally satisfied with the results)

1.3) Datasets¶

Amazon Alexa¶

  • Release dates [1]:</br> The release dates of Amazon Alexa for the different countries are covered by a table on the Wikipedia. I manually looked up the dates for the individual countries.

Baby Names¶

  • England and Wales [2] [3]:
    The GB Office for National Statistics provided their data in two different subsets: The first dataset covers the years 1907 to 1994, but contains only the top 100 names and only their sex and rank, not their count. The second dataset covers from 1996 to 2018 is more complete, covering much more names (with count >= 3) and provides gender, rank and counts. I wasn't able to identify datasets for the missing year 1995.

  • United States [4]:
    This dataset provided by the US Social Security Administration (SSA) seems quite complete: It contains information on name, sex, count and rank covers for every years from 1880 to 2018. The fact that it contains names with single occurcance (count=1) indicates, that all names are included.

  • Switzerland [5]:
    Provided by the Swizz Buro for Statistics, this dataset covers counts, ranks and sex for all names with at least 6 occurances in the year 2018, and reaches back to the year 1998.

  • New Zealand [6]:
    Covering the years from 1900 to 2019, this dataset by the Department of Internal Affairs and includes all names with at least 10 occurances together with their sex and count from 1900 to 2019.

  • Canada (Alberta) [7]:
    Canada doesn't provide national data, but some states publish their individual statistics. The dataset of Albert comes in a very data scientist friendly structure of a single table containing rank, count, year and sex for every names.

3.1) Download¶

In [4]:
def download_to_zip(urls, target_file):
    """Download files from list of urls and store in single zip file.

    This is done by directly streaming into the zip Object, without intermediate io.

    Arguments:
        urls {list} -- List of URLs to files
        target_file {PATH} -- Zip file to save
        
    """
    with ZipFile(target_file, "w") as zipObj:
        for url in urls:
            print(f"Get {'...' + url[-75:] if len(url) > 75 else url}")
            req = urllib.request.Request(url, headers={"User-Agent": "Mozilla/5.0"})
            resp = urllib.request.urlopen(req)
            stream = io.BytesIO()
            stream.write(resp.read())
            stream.seek(0)
            if resp.info().get_filename():
                fn = resp.info().get_filename()
            else:
                fn = url.split("/")[-1]
            zipObj.writestr(fn, stream.getvalue())
In [5]:
def download_datasets(overwrite=False):
    """Download all datasets and store them in the configured folders/files.

    This is done by directly streaming into the zip Object, without intermediate io.

    Arguments:
        overwrite {bool} -- Skip download, if target file exists
        
    """
    # Create data folder, if necessary
    DATA_PATH.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)

    # Download and store files
    for name, dataset in DATASETS.items():
        print(f"Downloading {name}-dataset:")

        target_file = DATA_PATH / dataset["filename"]
        if target_file.exists() and not overwrite:
            print(f"Skipped download: {target_file} already exists.")
            continue

        # Compile urls with prefix, in case its given
        urls = [dataset["url_prefix"] + u for u in dataset["urls"]]

        # Don't zip, if download contains already zipped files
        if dataset["urls"][0].endswith(".zip"):
            for url in urls:
                print(f"Get {'...' + url[-75:] if len(url) > 75 else url}")
                urllib.request.urlretrieve(url, target_file)
        else:
            download_to_zip(urls, target_file)

        print("Done.\n")

Helper functions for simple loading datasets into pandas DataFrame:

In [8]:
def gen_dataset_us():
    """Generator yielding on year from US dataset.
    
    This dataset is really simple to handle. One file per year.
    Only "rank" is missing and has to be calculated.

    Yields:
        {pd.DataFrame} -- Dataframe containing names of one year

    """
    file_path = DATA_PATH / DATASETS["US"]["filename"]
    with ZipFile(file_path, "r") as zip:
        files = [f for f in zip.namelist() if f.endswith(".txt")]
        for f in files:
            df = pd.read_csv(zip.open(f), names=["Name", "Sex", "Count"])
            df["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(int(f[3:7]), format="%Y")
            df["Dataset"] = "US"
            df["Rank"] = df.groupby("Sex")["Count"].rank(method="max", ascending=False)
            yield df
In [9]:
def gen_dataset_nz():
    """Generator yielding on year from NZ dataset.

    Also quite simple dataset. All data years are in single file. 
    Only "rank" is missing and has to be calculated.

    Yields:
        {pd.DataFrame} -- Dataframe containing names of one year

    """
    file_path = DATA_PATH / DATASETS["NZ"]["filename"]
    with ZipFile(file_path, "r") as zip:
        files = [f for f in zip.namelist() if f.endswith(".csv")]
        for f in files:
            df = pd.read_csv(zip.open(f), encoding="ISO-8859-2")
            df["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Year"], format="%Y")
            df["Dataset"] = "NZ"
            df["Rank"] = df.groupby(["Year", "Sex"])["Count"].rank(
                method="max", ascending=False
            )
            yield df
In [10]:
def gen_dataset_ch():
    """Generator yielding on year from CH dataset.

    More complicated Dataset. Data is split in two files for the different genders.
    Also the different years are provided as columns, with subcolumns for "rank" and "count".

    Yields:
        {pd.DataFrame} -- Dataframe containing names multiple years and one gender

    """
    file_path = DATA_PATH / DATASETS["CH"]["filename"]
    with ZipFile(file_path, "r") as zip:
        files = [f for f in zip.namelist() if f.endswith(".xlsx")]
        for fn in files:
            df = pd.read_excel(zip.open(fn), sheet_name=0, header=[2, 3], skipfooter=5)

            # Rename columns
            col_mapping = {
                "Vornamen": "Name",
                "Unnamed: 0_level_1": "Name",
                "Unnamed: 0_level_0": "Name",
                "Rang": "Rank",
                "Anzahl": "Count",
            }
            df = df.rename(columns=col_mapping, level=0).rename(
                columns=col_mapping, level=1
            )

            # Read columns year by year
            year_cols = list(df.columns.levels[0])
            year_cols.remove("Name")

            for col in year_cols:
                df_year = df[["Name", col]].copy()
                df_year.columns = df_year.columns.droplevel(level=0)
                df_year["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(col, format="%Y")
                df_year["Dataset"] = "CH"
                if fn == "su-d-01.04.00.01.xlsx":
                    df_year["Sex"] = "F"
                else:
                    df_year["Sex"] = "M"

                yield df_year
In [11]:
def gen_dataset_ca():
    """Generator yielding on year from CA dataset.
    
    Best structured dataset. Single file, containing _all_ needed datapoints. 

    Yields:
        {pd.DataFrame} -- Dataframe containing names multiple years and one gender

    """
    file_path = DATA_PATH / DATASETS["CA"]["filename"]
    with ZipFile(file_path, "r") as zip:
        files = [f for f in zip.namelist() if f.endswith(".xlsx")]
        for fn in files:
            df = pd.read_excel(
                zip.open(fn),
                sheet_name=0,
                header=5,
                names=["Rank", "Name", "Count", "Sex", "Year"],
            )
            df["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Year"], format="%Y")
            df["Sex"] = df["Sex"].replace({"Boy": "M", "Girl": "F"})
            df["Dataset"] = "CA"
            yield df

def gen_dataset_en_wls():
    """Generator yielding on year from GB dataset.
    
    Worst structured dataset. Contains different files, with two different structures.
    Data is spread over multiple sheets and inconsistently positioned.
    
    Yields:
        {pd.DataFrame} -- Dataframe containing names of one year

    """

    def _map_year_sheet(year):
        if year == 1996:
            return 3
        elif year <= 2010:
            return 6
        else:
            return 8

    def _map_year_header(year):
        if year <= 2008:
            return 5
        elif year <= 2016:
            return 4
        else:
            return 5

    def _map_year_cols(year):
        if year <= 2016:
            return [1, 2, 3]
        else:
            return [0, 1, 2]

    def _load_historic(zip, fn, sheet):
        df = pd.read_excel(zip.open(fn), sheet_name=sheet, header=3, skipfooter=2)
        # Drop empty first row
        df = df.dropna()
        # Unpivot
        df = df.melt(id_vars=["RANK"], value_vars=[1904])
        # Rename Columns
        df.columns = ["Rank", "Year", "Name"]
        # Normalize Casing
        df["Name"] = df["Name"].str.title().str.strip()
        # Cast Datatypes
        df["Rank"] = df["Rank"].astype(int)
        df["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(df["Year"], format="%Y")
        # Add Gender and Country information
        df["Sex"] = "M" if sheet == "Boys" else "F"
        df["Dataset"] = "EN, WLS"
        return df

    def _load_recent(zip, fn):
        year = int(fn[:4])
        df = pd.read_excel(
            zip.open(fn),
            sheet_name=_map_year_sheet(year),
            header=_map_year_header(year),
            usecols=_map_year_cols(year),
            names=["Rank", "Name", "Count"],
        )
        # Number of footer rows in xls varies, so sometimes we get empty rows
        df = df.dropna()
        # Normalize Casing
        df["Name"] = df["Name"].str.title().str.strip()
        # Cast Datatypes
        df[["Rank", "Count"]] = df[["Rank", "Count"]].astype(int)
        # Add year and gender (from filename), and country information
        df["Year"] = pd.to_datetime(year, format="%Y")
        df["Sex"] = "M" if "boys" in fn else "F"
        df["Dataset"] = "EN, WLS"
        return df

    file_path = DATA_PATH / DATASETS["EN, WLS"]["filename"]
    with ZipFile(file_path, "r") as zip:
        files = [fn for fn in zip.namelist() if fn.endswith(".xls")]
        for fn in files:
            if fn.startswith("historicname"):
                yield _load_historic(zip, fn, "Boys")
                yield _load_historic(zip, fn, "Girls")
            if fn[:4].isdigit():
                yield _load_recent(zip, fn)
In [13]:
def load_datasets(names):
    """Helper function to load all datasets into single dataframe.

    This also brings all datasets into the same form.

    Arguments:
        name {list} -- List of dataset short names, according to DATASETS. 

    Returns:
        {pd.DataFrame} -- All datasets in a single dataframe

    """
    list_dfs = []

    # Load individual Datasets
    if "US" in names or "all" in names:
        list_dfs.extend(gen_dataset_us())

    if "EN, WLS" in names or "all" in names:
        list_dfs.extend(gen_dataset_en_wls())

    if "CH" in names or "all" in names:
        list_dfs.extend(gen_dataset_ch())

    if "NZ" in names or "all" in names:
        list_dfs.extend(gen_dataset_nz())

    if "CA" in names or "all" in names:
        list_dfs.extend(gen_dataset_ca())

    # Merge list of dataframes into single dataframe
    df_all = pd.concat(list_dfs, axis=0, ignore_index=True, sort=False)

    return df_all

def add_description(ax):
    """Helper function that draws the decriptional text on the left side.
    
    Arguments:
        ax {matplotlib.Axis} -- Axis to draw the text on.
    
    """
    # Remove grid lines and axis
    ax.grid(False)
    ax.get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
    ax.get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)

    # Set background color
    ax.patch.set_facecolor(CANVAS_COLOR)

    # Define fonts
    alexa_font = font_manager.FontProperties(fname=str(font_file.resolve()), size=72)
    alexa_font_small = font_manager.FontProperties(
        fname=str(font_file.resolve()), size=42
    )

    # Set font properties
    font_dict = {
        "fontstretch": "condensed",
        "color": "white",
        "verticalalignment": "top",
    }

    # Draw text in three portions:
    ax.text(
        0, 1.01, "Hey            ,", fontproperties=alexa_font, fontdict=font_dict,
    )
    ax.text(
        0,
        0.83,
        "how many babies\nare named after you?",
        fontproperties=alexa_font_small,
        fontdict=font_dict,
        linespacing=1.4,
    )
    font_dict["color"] = ALEXA_BLUE  # Update text color
    ax.text(0, 1.01, "         Alexa", fontproperties=alexa_font, fontdict=font_dict)

def plot_dataset(dataset, ax, plot_no):
    """Plot data of a single dataset.
    
    Arguments:
        dataset {str} -- Name/key of the dataset to plot.
        ax {matplotlib.Axis} -- Axis to draw the chart on.
        plot_no {list} -- Indicates the position of the plot and count of all plots (pos, count).
    
    """

    # Filter data to given dataset
    df_alexa_dataset = df_alexa[df_alexa["Dataset"] == dataset]

    # Plot Datapoints
    ax.plot(
        df_alexa_dataset["Year"],
        df_alexa_dataset["Rank"],
        color="white",
        marker="o",
        markersize=5,
    )

    # Adjust background color
    ax.patch.set_facecolor(BG_COLOR)

    # Configure X-Axis
    ax.set_xlim("1998-01-01", "2020-01-01")
    ax.xaxis.tick_top()
    ax.set_xlabel("")

    # Configure Y-Axis
    ax.set_ylim(0, df_alexa_dataset["Rank"].max() * 1.1)
    ax.invert_yaxis()
    h = ax.set_ylabel(
        f"{DATASETS[dataset]['description']}",
        color="#888888",
        labelpad=10,
        size=12,
        verticalalignment="top",
        horizontalalignment="left",
        weight="bold",
    )
    h.set_rotation(0)
    ax.get_yaxis().set_label_coords(0.01, 0.95)

    # Grid lines
    ax.grid(b=True, which="major", color="#3c4043", linestyle="-")
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_color(BG_COLOR)
    ax.spines["left"].set_color("white")
    ax.spines["top"].set_color("white")
    ax.spines["right"].set_color(BG_COLOR)

    # Texts
    ax.tick_params(colors="white")

    # Plot release line
    if dataset == "CH":
        # Handle Swiss differently, as Alexa wasn't released there, yet
        white_line = plt.Line2D(
            (0, 1), (0, 0), color="white", marker="o", label="Rank of baby name 'Alexa'"
        )
        blue_line = plt.Line2D(
            (0, 1), (0, 0), color=ALEXA_BLUE, label="Release of Amazon Alexa"
        )
        release_text = "not yet"
    else:
        ax.axvline(x=DATASETS[dataset]["release"], color=ALEXA_BLUE, linewidth=1.3)
        release_text = DATASETS[dataset]["release"]

    # Add release dates
    ax.annotate(
        s=release_text,
        size=10,
        xy=(DATASETS[dataset]["release"], max(df_alexa_dataset["Rank"])),
        xytext=(-5, -5),
        color=ALEXA_BLUE,
        horizontalalignment="right",
        verticalalignment="bottom",
        textcoords="offset points",
    )

    # Hide x-ticks for all but first plot
    if plot_no[0] != 0:
        ax.get_xaxis().set_ticklabels([])
        ax.tick_params(axis="x", colors=CANVAS_COLOR)

    # Plot legend after last plot
    if plot_no[0] == plot_no[1] - 1:
        legend = plt.legend(
            handles=[white_line, blue_line],
            loc="upper center",
            fancybox=True,
            facecolor=BG_COLOR,
            edgecolor="#3c4043",
            ncol=2,
            bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, -0.2),
        )
        plt.setp(legend.get_texts(), color="w")

In this step, I also add the Echo picture, and the reference text in the lower left.

In [32]:
def convert_fig_to_img(fig):
    """Converts matplotlib figure into PIL image.
    
    Arguments:
        fig {matplotlib.Figure} -- Figure containing chart.
        
    Returns:
        {PIL.Image} -- Figure as PIL Image.
    """
    buf = io.BytesIO()
    fig.savefig(buf, format="png", facecolor=CANVAS_COLOR)
    buf.seek(0)
    im = Image.open(buf).copy()
    buf.close()
    return im
In [33]:
def add_margin(im, top, right, bottom, left, color):
    """Adds a margin to an PIL image.
    
    Arguments:
        pil_img {PIL.Image} -- Input image.
        top, right, bottom, left {int} -- Margin widths.
        color {str} -- Color of the margin.
        
    Returns:
        {PIL.Image} -- Output image with border.
    
    """
    width, height = im.size
    new_width = width + right + left
    new_height = height + top + bottom
    result = Image.new(im.mode, (new_width, new_height), color)
    result.paste(im, (left, top))
    return result
In [34]:
def add_reference_text(im, left, bottom):
    """Adds small text containing source information at bottom right.
    
    Arguments:
        im {PIL.Image} -- Input image.
        left, bottom {int} -- Position of text.        
        
    Returns:
        {PIL.Image} -- Output image with border.
        
    """
    draw = ImageDraw.Draw(im)
    font = ImageFont.truetype(str(font_file.resolve()), size=12)
    draw.text(
        (left, im.size[1] - bottom),
        "Created by Dynobo in 02/2020. Sourcecode, documentation and data sources: https://github.com/dynobo/notebooks/2020-02-Alexa.ipynb",
        fill="#6C7378",
        font=font,
    )
    return im
In [35]:
def add_echo_picture(im, left, top):
    """Adds picture of Amazon Echo.
    
    Arguments:
        im {PIL.Image} -- Input image.
        pos {tuple} -- Left and top position.
        
    Returns:
        {PIL.Image} -- Output image with border.
        
    """
    img_echo_png = Image.open("./assets/alexa/echo.png")
    img_echo_png = img_echo_png.resize((250, 250), Image.ANTIALIAS)
    img_echo = Image.new("RGBA", img_echo_png.size, CANVAS_COLOR)
    img_echo.paste(img_echo_png, (0, 0), img_echo_png)
    im.paste(img_echo, (left, top))
    return im
